00:28:31.310 --> 00:28:35.620
This time we're going to bring
the dam in from the wall.

00:28:35.620 --> 00:28:38.470
And we're going to
put a tiny opening.

00:28:38.470 --> 00:28:41.540
And I'm going to go
some more into the tank.

00:28:41.540 --> 00:28:42.890
And then another tiny opening.

00:28:42.890 --> 00:28:43.794
It could be the same.

00:28:43.794 --> 00:28:45.835
It's probably best to keep
it the same dimension.

00:28:48.700 --> 00:28:59.030
Now, in this case, the spacing,
d, is much less than lambda.

00:28:59.030 --> 00:29:00.960
d is much less than lambda.

00:29:00.960 --> 00:29:02.590
And what happens in this case?

00:29:02.590 --> 00:29:05.430
When d is much less than lambda,
you don't get the shadow.

00:29:05.430 --> 00:29:07.780
You don't get something
like this instead, remember.

00:29:07.780 --> 00:29:08.760
You've got the rings.

00:29:11.840 --> 00:29:15.170
This is called diffraction.

00:29:15.170 --> 00:29:16.880
Diffraction.

00:29:16.880 --> 00:29:21.620
And there is no way to
explain diffraction modeling

00:29:21.620 --> 00:29:23.750
water as a beam.

00:29:23.750 --> 00:29:28.500
You must implore the
wave-like behavior of water

00:29:28.500 --> 00:29:31.450
in order to explain diffraction.

00:29:31.450 --> 00:29:40.010
Explain only by invoking
wave-like properties.

00:29:43.250 --> 00:29:47.370
So with wave-like properties, we
get something that makes sense

00:29:47.370 --> 00:29:50.160
in terms of the data.

00:29:50.160 --> 00:29:52.320
Now, let's do this
same experiment,

00:29:52.320 --> 00:29:54.790
let's do this same experiment
on a metal crystal.

00:29:54.790 --> 00:29:57.940
So if you go back to
the gas discharge tube.

00:29:57.940 --> 00:30:01.120
Remember the gas discharge
tube that we were looking

00:30:01.120 --> 00:30:04.020
at for lecture after lecture?

00:30:04.020 --> 00:30:08.280
If you take a look and go
through the energetics of it.

00:30:08.280 --> 00:30:10.740
If you put one volt
across the plates,

00:30:10.740 --> 00:30:13.240
you know the energy is going
to be a product of charge times

00:30:13.240 --> 00:30:13.870
voltage.

00:30:13.870 --> 00:30:17.210
And that's equal
to 1/2 mv squared.

00:30:17.210 --> 00:30:20.250
Which you know from 801
is p squared over 2m.

00:30:20.250 --> 00:30:23.670
And p is equal to h over lambda.

00:30:23.670 --> 00:30:26.580
Pretty soon you can come
up with the wavelength.

00:30:26.580 --> 00:30:29.240
And that will give you the
wavelength of the electron.

00:30:29.240 --> 00:30:31.410
This is a ballistic
electron now.

00:30:31.410 --> 00:30:32.640
See what I'm doing?

00:30:32.640 --> 00:30:35.860
See, once I said
that this indicates

00:30:35.860 --> 00:30:37.980
that the electronic
in stationary orbit

00:30:37.980 --> 00:30:41.450
can be modeled as a wave
of a certain wavelength, so

00:30:41.450 --> 00:30:43.750
now the free electron.

00:30:43.750 --> 00:30:46.680
It's got m, it's got v,
there's Planck constant.

00:30:46.680 --> 00:30:49.130
I can go ahead and
compute its wavelength.

00:30:49.130 --> 00:30:52.630
I can compute the
wavelength of a baseball.

00:30:52.630 --> 00:30:54.130
So, you go through it.

00:30:54.130 --> 00:30:58.970
And you get a value
of about 12 Angstroms.

00:30:58.970 --> 00:30:59.850
12 Angstroms.

00:30:59.850 --> 00:31:05.080
Now, if I want to see whether
there's wave-like properties,

00:31:05.080 --> 00:31:07.850
I need to have a condition
that gives me diffraction.

00:31:07.850 --> 00:31:09.670
So I'm going to have
to find something

00:31:09.670 --> 00:31:13.160
that gives me a dam
with an opening that's

00:31:13.160 --> 00:31:15.840
less than 12 Angstroms.

00:31:15.840 --> 00:31:19.960
If I'm going to use 1 volt.

00:31:19.960 --> 00:31:21.170
So what can I do?

00:31:21.170 --> 00:31:24.190
Well, turns out you're going
to learn this in greater detail

00:31:24.190 --> 00:31:27.200
later, but if this is
a crystal of nickel.

00:31:27.200 --> 00:31:30.890
Crystal of nickel, the atoms
are arranged in regular arrays.

00:31:30.890 --> 00:31:34.550
And this is what the face of
nickel looks like, 4 atoms each

00:31:34.550 --> 00:31:35.410
at the corner.

00:31:35.410 --> 00:31:37.190
And one in the
center of that face.

00:31:37.190 --> 00:31:41.040
This distance is 3.53 Angstroms.

00:31:41.040 --> 00:31:42.490
Perfect.

00:31:42.490 --> 00:31:43.170
Perfect.

00:31:43.170 --> 00:31:49.230
So what Davisson and Germer
did is, they irradiated this.

00:31:49.230 --> 00:31:54.590
They irradiated this first with
X-rays on the order of lambda,

00:31:54.590 --> 00:31:58.090
on the order of,
say, 10 Angstroms.

00:31:58.090 --> 00:31:59.960
And what did they get?

00:31:59.960 --> 00:32:01.230
This is the output.

00:32:01.230 --> 00:32:02.130
This is the output.

00:32:02.130 --> 00:32:05.620
You get a diffraction pattern.

00:32:05.620 --> 00:32:07.940
It's a set of rings,
concentric rings.

00:32:07.940 --> 00:32:13.090
So this is the
X-ray diffraction.

00:32:13.090 --> 00:32:17.520
This is the X-ray
diffractogram, if you like.

00:32:17.520 --> 00:32:20.140
And then, what did they do next?

00:32:20.140 --> 00:32:25.325
They irradiate the same
crystal with an electron beam.

00:32:27.990 --> 00:32:32.930
lambda of the electron
beam, 10 Angstroms.

00:32:32.930 --> 00:32:35.230
And what did they get?

00:32:35.230 --> 00:32:36.220
Are you ready?

00:32:36.220 --> 00:32:36.910
Drum roll.

00:32:40.140 --> 00:32:44.140
Now, there is no way
that you can get a ring

00:32:44.140 --> 00:32:49.670
pattern from a beam of electrons
acting as a particle beam.

00:32:49.670 --> 00:32:53.550
The only explanation for
this is that the electrons

00:32:53.550 --> 00:32:58.020
were behaving as
waves of this value

00:32:58.020 --> 00:33:01.260
to give us the same spacing
as we got with X-rays.

00:33:01.260 --> 00:33:04.430
And you're comfortable
if I say that X-rays

00:33:04.430 --> 00:33:07.050
are a type of light.

00:33:07.050 --> 00:33:09.680
So, therefore, it's got
wave-like properties.

00:33:09.680 --> 00:33:11.280
And it's got
particle-like properties.

00:33:11.280 --> 00:33:12.700
Well, now I've
just made the point

00:33:12.700 --> 00:33:16.820
that this is the
electron diffractogram.

00:33:16.820 --> 00:33:21.710
So this is evidence of
electron diffraction.

00:33:21.710 --> 00:33:23.210
And this shook the world.

00:33:23.210 --> 00:33:24.680
Because now it's real.

00:33:24.680 --> 00:33:27.190
There's no way you can
get this otherwise.

00:33:27.190 --> 00:33:31.970
This is electron diffraction.

00:33:31.970 --> 00:33:33.720
This was 1927.

00:33:33.720 --> 00:33:37.110
1929, de Broglie
gets the Nobel Prize.

00:33:37.110 --> 00:33:42.540
1937, Davisson gets
the Nobel Prize.

00:33:42.540 --> 00:33:47.710
So this means the wave-particle
duality is complete.

00:33:47.710 --> 00:33:52.130
It applies not only to light,
but it applies to matter.

00:33:52.130 --> 00:33:57.200
So, wave-particle
duality, they call it.

00:33:57.200 --> 00:33:59.665
Wave-particle
duality is complete.

00:34:02.770 --> 00:34:05.640
Matter can act as waves.

00:34:05.640 --> 00:34:08.710
Electromagnetic radiation
can act as particles.

00:34:08.710 --> 00:34:12.230
So, sometimes people refer to
de Broglie's accomplishment

00:34:12.230 --> 00:34:15.370
as matter waves.

00:34:15.370 --> 00:34:15.974
Matter waves.

00:34:18.810 --> 00:34:23.530
And what do you call the
behavior of billiard balls

00:34:23.530 --> 00:34:24.700
banging around and so on?

00:34:24.700 --> 00:34:26.500
We call that mechanics.

00:34:26.500 --> 00:34:28.850
So now we're going
to use what might

00:34:28.850 --> 00:34:32.930
seem as an oxymoron,
contradiction, wave mechanics.

00:34:32.930 --> 00:34:36.120
Wave mechanics.

00:34:36.120 --> 00:34:38.680
That means matter
behaving as a wave.

00:34:38.680 --> 00:34:40.480
But still behaving as a matter.

00:34:40.480 --> 00:34:42.200
So this is the dynamic.

00:34:42.200 --> 00:34:48.170
So that's pretty
good for de Broglie.

00:34:48.170 --> 00:34:49.650
So let's go to number two.

00:34:49.650 --> 00:34:51.649
I said there were going
to be three people here.

00:34:51.649 --> 00:34:54.270
Number two is Werner Heisenberg.

00:34:54.270 --> 00:34:55.020
Werner Heisenberg.

00:34:58.820 --> 00:35:01.640
Heisenberg studied with Pauli.

00:35:04.260 --> 00:35:06.960
Sommerfeld.

00:35:06.960 --> 00:35:10.290
Did his Ph.D in Munich in 1923.

00:35:10.290 --> 00:35:14.750
Got his Ph.D with
Sommerfeld at the age of 22.

00:35:14.750 --> 00:35:17.765
And then he decided to
take a postdoc with Bohr.

00:35:17.765 --> 00:35:19.890
And he was working with
Bohr for a couple of years,

00:35:19.890 --> 00:35:22.020
he was feeling a
little bit burned-out.

00:35:22.020 --> 00:35:24.820
And decided to take
three weeks off.

00:35:24.820 --> 00:35:28.590
Went up to a deserted island
off the coast of Norway.

00:35:28.590 --> 00:35:31.450
Came back three weeks later with
the mathematical formulation

00:35:31.450 --> 00:35:33.700
of quantum mechanics.

00:35:33.700 --> 00:35:36.950
I'm not kidding you, that's
what he did in his time

00:35:36.950 --> 00:35:39.330
off, to kind of unwind.

00:35:39.330 --> 00:35:44.650
And so one of the things that
he used as a critical piece

00:35:44.650 --> 00:35:49.350
of this derivation is that
the position and velocity

00:35:49.350 --> 00:35:53.000
of an electron cannot
be fully specified.

00:35:53.000 --> 00:35:56.470
They cannot be fully specified
below certain limits.

00:35:56.470 --> 00:35:59.590
There's a threshold
below which we can't go.

00:35:59.590 --> 00:36:01.500
This is sort of
like, if I asked you

00:36:01.500 --> 00:36:04.960
to time a 100-meter
sprint, which typically

00:36:04.960 --> 00:36:06.670
takes less than 10 seconds.

00:36:06.670 --> 00:36:09.680
But I give you a clock, and
the nearest unit on the clock

00:36:09.680 --> 00:36:10.910
is the minute.

00:36:10.910 --> 00:36:13.740
So you wouldn't be
able to distinguish.

00:36:13.740 --> 00:36:16.020
So, he says-- and
the reason for this

00:36:16.020 --> 00:36:18.580
is, it's a consequence
of quantization.

00:36:18.580 --> 00:36:20.340
Light itself is quantized.

00:36:20.340 --> 00:36:24.770
So, at some point you're asking
for a continuous splitting

00:36:24.770 --> 00:36:27.400
and splitting and splitting into
finer and finer time segments.

00:36:27.400 --> 00:36:28.400
And you can't get there.

00:36:28.400 --> 00:36:30.650
So we already knew
this from Planck.

00:36:30.650 --> 00:36:35.580
And so one of the ways that
he expressed the inability

00:36:35.580 --> 00:36:41.360
to go below a certain threshold
is the uncertainty principle.

00:36:41.360 --> 00:36:43.220
The uncertainty principle.

00:36:43.220 --> 00:36:44.820
And that's
unfortunate that, see,

00:36:44.820 --> 00:36:46.580
it was originally
published in German.

00:36:46.580 --> 00:36:51.170
And the idea really is the
indeterminacy principle.

00:36:51.170 --> 00:36:53.220
But, English says uncertainty.

00:36:53.220 --> 00:36:57.350
So it's a limit to
determination, but there it is.

00:36:57.350 --> 00:36:59.410
And so one expression
of this is,

00:36:59.410 --> 00:37:01.310
the product of the velocity.

00:37:01.310 --> 00:37:03.284
Only, he wrote it in
terms of momentum.

00:37:03.284 --> 00:37:04.700
So the mass isn't
going to change.

00:37:04.700 --> 00:37:08.460
So, think of this as the
uncertainty and the velocity.

00:37:08.460 --> 00:37:10.350
And the uncertainty
in the position.

00:37:10.350 --> 00:37:13.290
So this is the
x-coordinate of particle.

00:37:13.290 --> 00:37:15.780
You can break its
trajectory into three

00:37:15.780 --> 00:37:16.910
orthogonal components.

00:37:16.910 --> 00:37:19.030
So the uncertainty
in the x direction

00:37:19.030 --> 00:37:23.290
of the momentum times the
uncertainty in the position

00:37:23.290 --> 00:37:27.550
is greater than or equal to
the Planck constant divided

00:37:27.550 --> 00:37:28.940
by 2 pi.

00:37:28.940 --> 00:37:30.800
The Planck constant
divided by 2 pi.

00:37:33.725 --> 00:37:35.800
And so what this
means is that we're

00:37:35.800 --> 00:37:41.635
going to see a transition in
models from individual atoms.

00:37:44.160 --> 00:37:47.810
If we want to describe what
happens with individual atoms,

00:37:47.810 --> 00:37:50.330
we need what is known as
a deterministic model.

00:37:50.330 --> 00:37:51.790
Sort of, Newtonian mechanics.

00:37:51.790 --> 00:37:54.025
You tell me the initial
position and velocity.

00:37:54.025 --> 00:37:56.570
You tell me the forces, and I
can predict where it's going

00:37:56.570 --> 00:37:57.695
and where it's going to be.

00:37:57.695 --> 00:38:01.460
So that's deterministic models.

00:38:01.460 --> 00:38:06.730
So, deterministic models
describing individual atoms

00:38:06.730 --> 00:38:13.790
are going to give rise
to probabilistic models.

00:38:17.150 --> 00:38:19.390
Probabilistic models.

00:38:19.390 --> 00:38:21.110
And probabilistic
models obviously

00:38:21.110 --> 00:38:22.970
can't be talking about
individual atoms.

00:38:22.970 --> 00:38:25.760
Must be talking about
ensembles of atoms.

00:38:28.360 --> 00:38:30.560
So I can't say where any
individual atom will be,

00:38:30.560 --> 00:38:33.240
because I don't have
the ability to do so.

00:38:33.240 --> 00:38:36.280
But I can tell you, if you
give me a large number of them,

00:38:36.280 --> 00:38:39.440
I'll tell you roughly
what the expected outcome

00:38:39.440 --> 00:38:40.680
could be in terms of energy.

00:38:40.680 --> 00:38:43.670
And ultimately predict
the spectrum, and so on.

00:38:43.670 --> 00:38:45.280
So instead of chicken
and egg we have

00:38:45.280 --> 00:38:47.810
now chickenality and egg-ness.

00:38:47.810 --> 00:38:51.060
Everything is just sort of
getting a little bit murky.

00:38:51.060 --> 00:38:51.890
Little bit murky.

00:38:51.890 --> 00:38:53.770
You can do a
calculation on this.

00:38:53.770 --> 00:38:56.490
You can do a calculation on
this, a very simple take.

00:38:56.490 --> 00:39:00.110
Take the Bohr model and take
the ground state electron

00:39:00.110 --> 00:39:03.127
in hydrogen. n equals
1 in atomic hydrogen.

00:39:03.127 --> 00:39:04.960
And you know this is
about half an Angstrom.

00:39:04.960 --> 00:39:08.180
So the distance across
here is 1 Angstrom.

00:39:08.180 --> 00:39:12.610
So make 1 Angstrom
your uncertainty,

00:39:12.610 --> 00:39:19.040
and you'll find that the
uncertainty in the momentum

00:39:19.040 --> 00:39:21.100
is on the order of 15%.

00:39:24.005 --> 00:39:25.880
But what this is saying
is, when you get down

00:39:25.880 --> 00:39:29.200
to atomic dimensions, you
can't just shine light on it

00:39:29.200 --> 00:39:30.734
and reveal what's going on.

00:39:30.734 --> 00:39:32.650
Because you're going to
disturb the very thing

00:39:32.650 --> 00:39:34.240
you're trying to measure.

00:39:34.240 --> 00:39:36.870
Some people say
that, every time you

00:39:36.870 --> 00:39:38.750
try to work at the
atomic level, it's

00:39:38.750 --> 00:39:40.510
as though you're trying
to take a picture

00:39:40.510 --> 00:39:43.185
with the sun at your back and
your shadow is in the picture.

00:39:43.185 --> 00:39:48.445
So you can't get there without
disturbing the very thing.

00:39:48.445 --> 00:39:49.820
Another way to
think about it is,

00:39:49.820 --> 00:39:51.847
the photons that are
capable of this resolution

00:39:51.847 --> 00:39:53.680
are going to have such
high energies they'll

00:39:53.680 --> 00:39:56.070
knock the very thing
you're trying to measure.

00:39:56.070 --> 00:39:56.570
All right.

00:39:56.570 --> 00:40:00.680
He gets Nobel Prize in 1932.

00:40:00.680 --> 00:40:04.140
And then the third one
is Erwin Schroedinger.

00:40:04.140 --> 00:40:05.130
Let's get him up here.

00:40:09.110 --> 00:40:11.810
Erwin Schroedinger.

00:40:11.810 --> 00:40:14.640
Also an Austrian,
University of Zurich.

00:40:14.640 --> 00:40:16.480
He too was burned out.

00:40:16.480 --> 00:40:18.320
They get burned out, these guys.

00:40:18.320 --> 00:40:22.940
So at Christmastime,
1925, took a vacation.

00:40:22.940 --> 00:40:26.100
At Villa Herwig, in Aurora.

00:40:26.100 --> 00:40:31.580
And comes back two weeks
later with the wave mechanics

00:40:31.580 --> 00:40:35.150
formulation, of
quantum mechanics.

00:40:35.150 --> 00:40:37.940
See, sometimes going
away on a vacation.

00:40:37.940 --> 00:40:41.720
So he took de Broglie's notion
of the electron as a wave

00:40:41.720 --> 00:40:44.770
and wrote equations to
model wave-like behavior.

00:40:44.770 --> 00:40:48.535
So, let's look at
how to get there.

00:40:48.535 --> 00:40:51.850
And here's what he did.

00:40:51.850 --> 00:40:54.630
So, you know, for
example, that we could

00:40:54.630 --> 00:40:56.820
start with a violin string.

00:40:56.820 --> 00:40:58.660
And it has a
geometric constraint.

00:40:58.660 --> 00:41:00.560
It must be fixed at both ends.

00:41:00.560 --> 00:41:02.750
And if I pluck
that string, it can

00:41:02.750 --> 00:41:07.485
vibrate as long as it conforms
to the geometric constraint

00:41:07.485 --> 00:41:08.600
of a standing wave.

00:41:08.600 --> 00:41:11.210
So here's one possibility.

00:41:11.210 --> 00:41:13.160
Wherein we would
call this n equals 1.

00:41:13.160 --> 00:41:17.410
I have simply the
entire string vibrating

00:41:17.410 --> 00:41:18.930
in the matter that's shown.

00:41:18.930 --> 00:41:20.600
But here's a second possibility.

00:41:20.600 --> 00:41:23.030
I could have it vibrating
as is shown here,

00:41:23.030 --> 00:41:24.880
n equals 2 with a
node in the middle

00:41:24.880 --> 00:41:26.530
where that node
doesn't move at all.

00:41:26.530 --> 00:41:30.620
The string is stationary
at its mid-point.

00:41:30.620 --> 00:41:33.460
And what's the
characteristic here?

00:41:33.460 --> 00:41:36.160
This is operating at
a certain frequency.

00:41:36.160 --> 00:41:39.650
Let's say it's middle C.
And this is the overtone.

00:41:39.650 --> 00:41:41.400
This is the first harmonic.

00:41:41.400 --> 00:41:43.530
And it's going to
be an octave higher,

00:41:43.530 --> 00:41:47.050
because it's as though we
have two strings, each fixed.

00:41:47.050 --> 00:41:49.830
See, from a physics
standpoint I could literally

00:41:49.830 --> 00:41:53.100
cut this string in half and
fix it there, and this is now n

00:41:53.100 --> 00:41:55.380
equals 1 for the half-length.

00:41:55.380 --> 00:41:58.140
So it's going to have the
same pitch as the half-length.

00:41:58.140 --> 00:42:00.425
Which means that this
is an octave higher,

00:42:00.425 --> 00:42:02.990
and this is going to be two
octaves higher, and so on.

00:42:02.990 --> 00:42:04.520
And all of these conform.

00:42:04.520 --> 00:42:08.110
So you get a plurality
of solutions.

00:42:08.110 --> 00:42:10.890
You get a plurality
of solutions.

00:42:10.890 --> 00:42:13.780
And the solutions look
something like this.

00:42:13.780 --> 00:42:20.700
They'll eventually teach you
the string as a simple harmonic

00:42:20.700 --> 00:42:22.700
oscillator.

00:42:22.700 --> 00:42:27.960
Simple harmonic oscillator.

00:42:27.960 --> 00:42:31.540
And it has equations
that look like this.

00:42:31.540 --> 00:42:33.165
If you want to
plot its position,

