this is x going from 0 to l.

00:42:38.250 --> 00:42:40.650
And this is the y-coordinate.

00:42:40.650 --> 00:42:44.060
So you can, for example,
write something like this.

00:42:44.060 --> 00:42:48.380
So, the function
will look like this.

00:42:48.380 --> 00:42:52.320
Some pre-multiplier
times cosine of kx

00:42:52.320 --> 00:42:57.190
plus another pre-multiplier
b times the sine of kx.

00:42:57.190 --> 00:43:01.620
And the geometry will
dictate that the value of k

00:43:01.620 --> 00:43:03.720
is n pi over l.

00:43:03.720 --> 00:43:06.020
So, pi over l is the geometry.

00:43:06.020 --> 00:43:10.430
And n takes multiple values.

00:43:10.430 --> 00:43:13.940
Just as you see here, there's
not a unique solution.

00:43:13.940 --> 00:43:15.470
So listen carefully.

00:43:15.470 --> 00:43:19.690
Wave equation,
plurality of solutions.

00:43:19.690 --> 00:43:22.330
But subject to some constraints.

00:43:22.330 --> 00:43:23.670
Subject to some constraints.

00:43:23.670 --> 00:43:27.250
So what Schroedinger did
is, he wrote a wave equation

00:43:27.250 --> 00:43:33.720
to describe the motion
of electron in its orbit.

00:43:33.720 --> 00:43:35.210
And guess what he gets?

00:43:35.210 --> 00:43:37.860
He gets a plurality
of solutions.

00:43:37.860 --> 00:43:40.670
And when you look at the
plurality of solutions,

00:43:40.670 --> 00:43:42.870
the plurality of
solutions ultimately

00:43:42.870 --> 00:43:50.970
map into what we know as the
distinct values of n, l, m

00:43:50.970 --> 00:43:52.180
and s.

00:43:52.180 --> 00:43:54.030
See, this is the
one-dimensional.

00:43:54.030 --> 00:43:57.990
So this is giving us
n numbers. n equals 1,

00:43:57.990 --> 00:44:00.210
this is now n equals 2.

00:44:00.210 --> 00:44:02.020
So I'm getting
quantum numbers here.

00:44:02.020 --> 00:44:04.130
Now, if I did this
in three dimensions,

00:44:04.130 --> 00:44:06.040
I'd have a plurality
of quantum numbers.

00:44:06.040 --> 00:44:10.480
And Schroedinger gets us all
the way to n, l, m and s.

00:44:10.480 --> 00:44:13.010
And so here's what
it looks like.

00:44:13.010 --> 00:44:15.320
This is the equation,
it's a wave equation,

00:44:15.320 --> 00:44:18.480
so there's a double
derivative in space.

00:44:18.480 --> 00:44:19.700
There's a forcing function.

00:44:19.700 --> 00:44:23.070
And this is i, square root of
minus 1 in a time base here.

00:44:23.070 --> 00:44:26.610
So it's a harmonic
kind of equation.

00:44:26.610 --> 00:44:29.249
Psi is the wave function,
it's an abstract concept

00:44:29.249 --> 00:44:31.040
but we'll show you how
to make sense of it.

00:44:31.040 --> 00:44:33.940
And these are the
various solutions,

00:44:33.940 --> 00:44:35.480
the plurality of solutions.

00:44:35.480 --> 00:44:39.930
And we can now map those into
what we know as 1s, 2s, 2px,

00:44:39.930 --> 00:44:42.720
2py, 2pz, et cetera, et cetera.

00:44:42.720 --> 00:44:45.090
And you see this number a sub 0.

00:44:45.090 --> 00:44:46.660
That's our Bohr radius.

00:44:46.660 --> 00:44:48.710
Comes right out
of the equations.

00:44:48.710 --> 00:44:51.890
0.529 Angstroms.

00:44:51.890 --> 00:44:54.910
So, this is quite good.

00:44:54.910 --> 00:44:58.770
But, as I said, the psi
is the wave function.

00:44:58.770 --> 00:45:00.620
Or psi, however you
want to call this.

00:45:00.620 --> 00:45:03.090
This is called
the wave function.

00:45:03.090 --> 00:45:04.530
Wave function.

00:45:04.530 --> 00:45:07.005
And we have plurality
of solutions.

00:45:10.542 --> 00:45:11.750
We call these Eigenfunctions.

00:45:14.400 --> 00:45:15.840
Eigenfunctions.

00:45:15.840 --> 00:45:19.860
And the closest we can
get to something physical

00:45:19.860 --> 00:45:24.110
is the product of psi and
its complex conjugate.

00:45:24.110 --> 00:45:27.240
And that is related
to the probability

00:45:27.240 --> 00:45:29.560
of finding the electron.

00:45:29.560 --> 00:45:33.222
Probability of
finding the electron.

00:45:33.222 --> 00:45:36.180
Which, in essence, gives the
boundaries of the orbitals.

